I work on a project that uses tchannel-python and decorates a large number of tests with vcr.use_cassette to stub out tchannel calls.  It uses the same yaml file as a fixture everywhere it calls vcr.use_cassette.  It's a somewhat large yaml file; on my MacBook Pro, it takes about half a second to load/parse the file.

The issue is that each time vcr.use_cassette is called, the yaml file is loaded and parsed anew, adding at least 0.5 seconds to each test in the case above.  See [here](https://github.com/uber/tchannel-python/blob/master/tchannel/testing/vcr/cassette.py#L170):

```
    def _load(self):
        try:
            with open(self.path, 'rb') as f:
                data = f.read()
                self.existed = True
        except IOError:
            return  # nothing to read

        data = yaml.load(data)
        if not (data and 'interactions' in data):
            return  # file was probably empty

        if int(data['version']) != VERSION:
            raise UnsupportedVersionError(
                'Cassette at "%s" is an unsupported version of the '
                'format: version %s' % (self.path, str(data['version']))
            )

        self._available = [
            Interaction.to_native(i) for i in data['interactions']
        ]
```

I'd propose adding an optional cache for interactions loaded from a yaml file, so that users who have a read-only file used throughout their test suite can read/parse it once (rather than every time vcr.use_cassette is called).

I don't have a lot of experience with python, but the code would probably look something like this.  There'd be a cache class:

```
class _InteractionsCache(object):

    _cache = {}

    @classmethod
    def save_interactions(cls, path, interactions):
        cls._cache[path] = interactions

    @classmethod
    def load_interactions(cls, path):
        try:
            return deepcopy(cls._cache[path])
        except KeyError:
            return None

```

(Do I need to work about any sort of thread-safety issues with this kind of cache in Python?)

Then I'd modify Cassette._load (additions are the blocks starting with `if self.use_cache` at beginning and end of the method):

```
    def _load(self):
        if self.use_cache:
            interactions = _InteractionsCache.load_interactions(self.path)
            if interactions:
                self._available = interactions
                return

        try:
            with open(self.path, 'rb') as f:
                data = f.read()
                self.existed = True
        except IOError:
            return  # nothing to read

        data = yaml.load(data)
        if not (data and 'interactions' in data):
            return  # file was probably empty

        if int(data['version']) != VERSION:
            raise UnsupportedVersionError(
                'Cassette at "%s" is an unsupported version of the '
                'format: version %s' % (self.path, str(data['version']))
            )

        self._available = [
            Interaction.to_native(i) for i in data['interactions']
        ]
        if self.use_cache:
            _InteractionsCache.save_interactions(self.path, self._available)

```

Let me know if this seems like a reasonable idea and approach and I can put out a PR.  Any comments/suggestions/criticisms would be greatly appreciated.

